{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8c7ea33-1e4f-4bce-b9f5-0d1bee09af9c","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events** API in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder setup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // Runs when Android activity is paused\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // Runs when Android activity is stopped\n        }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // Runs when iOS app enters background\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` is called on the `MauiAppBuilder`.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code compile-safe.\n- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.\n- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.\n- You can chain multiple handlers on the same platform builder.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fcb34685-9f4d-440a-b87c-1a1eba6d3c1f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":397},"id":"4ed664f5-49f9-44f8-8314-4b36dbcda134","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:39:56.321Z","parentId":"bf99c9c9-9be9-4423-8442-75b627b522c0"}
